<div id="c2">
<p>Hey Aaron! I remember that day at MIT :)</p>

<p>Regarding: &#8220;But I can take you to meet our PR director and she can answer any questions you might have.&#8221; / This seemed like an odd move to me. &#8230; some back story re the &#8216;odd&#8217;ness:</p>

<p>Before you stopped by, we&#8217;d mentioned (by way of the RSS1 collaboration) that we&#8217;d both be around at same time, and talked about meeting.</p>

<p>When I mentioned this to a Rael (who was chairing the RSS1 cabal) he said something like &#8220;oh., erm, so you&#8217;re going to meet a teenage boy off the Internet?&#8221;, suggesting that US lawpersons might soon have me locked up if I wasn&#8217;t more careful, or if parents/police found out you were meeting an Internet Stranger. This hadn&#8217;t occured to me, but on that advice I didn&#8217;t rush to arrange a meeting.  I was new to the USA and its strange ways, after all.</p>

<p>So I was a little suprised when you turned up unannounced at MIT :) - though it was nice to see you. We were having an Annotea meeting at the time, I think. So one motivation to meet with PR / head-of-comms was to offset Rael&#8217;s concern.</p>

<p>Also she was more entertaining than me. The little rant you triggered was by asking something like &#8220;so why is the W3C all closed and secret, while the IETF are open and public?&#8221;. At which point you got the same treatment anyone else would&#8217;ve gotten if they asked the same.</p>

<p>Anyways it was good meeting you and having you in the RDFCore WG. I do think you&#8217;ve got the wrong impression of RRS though, so sorry to hear that.</p>

<p>All the best,</p>

<p>Dan</p>

<p class="posted">posted by <a rel="nofollow" href="http://danbri.org/">Dan Brickley</a>
